Foliar feeding is always my favorite way to fertilize plants. Anytime I notice any deficiency in plants, it’s my go-to method to address the issue quickly. 
Dilute your fertilizer and spray it on the leaves. Plants can absorb minerals and nutrients through tiny pores in their leaves called the stomata.
You can apply any organic fertilizer or amendments this way, like compost tea, vermicompost tea, kelp, fish emulsion, or more.

Overwintering pepper plants is not something that I do often. With the climate down here in Houston, it’s not necessary. For some reason this year I felt like keeping these two ghost pepper plants Even though I wish they were scotch bonnets instead. 

Overwintering helps you get a head start on your next pepper growing season. Whether it’s spring or summer. 

This process works because peppers are actually perennials. Meaning that if they don’t experience a freeze they will continue produce for multiple seasons. 

How to overwinter pepper plants 
1. Dig up the pepper from the garden bed 
2. Clean off excess soil from the roots 
3. Transplant pepper into a pot filled with high quality organic soil like @heirloom soils 
4. Cut the pepper back leaving only a few main branches 
5. Water 
6. Keep in a warm spot until the weather is suitable for planting 

#justgrowit #gardentips #gardeningtips #wintergarden #zone9garden #gardeninglife #pepperplants

Do you plant your carrots in neat rows or scatter the seeds randomly over the garden bed?

I think every gardener should grow carrots, regardless of the size of their garden. 

If you’re short on space in your raised beds, don’t sweat. You can grow carrots in containers. The key to success in containers is to ensure you have the right size container for your variety. 

Carrot growing tips: 
1. Remember to keep the soil loose
2. Stay away from nitrogen-rich fertilizers
3. Overseed the planting area
4. Thin the seedlings as they emerge
5. Be patient ✌🏾

#justgrowit #alwaysgrowingfood #growyourownfood #gardenlife #urbangardener #backyardgarden #houstongarden #raisedbedgarden #vegogarden

Intensive planting is a way of spacing crops to produce and harvest as much as possible from an allotted space. It is not just about plant spacing. It also takes into account things such as growth pattern, size of the plant at maturity, shade tolerance, nutrient needs, and growing season. 

If you’re short on growing space like me and other urban gardeners, intensive planting will help you get the most out of your garden ✌🏾

Every year I forget to plant peas, but Not this year. 

Peas have tendeils and want to grow vertically. When growing peas, plant them close to a trellis at least 6’ long. 

One of the best things about peas is that you don’t have to pay too much attention to spacing. This is because whether I thin the peas or not, I still seem to get the same harvests. 

Maybe I will thin one side and not thin the other and see the difference. 🤷🏾‍♂️

I have a confession. I secret to love beets. And ever since I started to JUST GROW IT, I have been trying to grow beets that look like the ones I see in the produce aisles. 

Beets are a cool season crop that many people exclude from their fall/winter garden, and I’m not sure why. 

In the last beet video, I showed you a tip of soaking the beets overnight to improve their germination rate. After soaking your beets, it’s time to get them in the ground. You can remove the seeds from the water and plant them normally, or you can pour the seeds while they are still in the water into your garden. The choice is yours. 

This year I’m experimenting to see if the seeds I soaked perform better than those I did not. I think I will only notice a faster germination rate. 

Let’s see. 

#justgrowit #urbangardener #gardentips #wintergardening #growyourownfood #houstongardener

I hate whenever I walk out to the garden and notice leaves that have been chewed.

Caterpillars are usually most active at night or early in the morning. Often you can catch me outside with a flashlight in the middle of the night searching for caterpillars.

I have noticed in the beds where I leave a lot of debris, I tend to find more caterpillars. This is a good reason to keep your beds cleaned and mulched✌🏾

1.5 billion tons of food is wasted every year. Stats say that between 80-119 billion pounds of that waste came from the US. When you say that number out loud, it is shocking. 

As an urban gardener and lover of the earth, I need to do my part to help minimize food waste that goes to a landfill and creates another issue. 

Before moving, I was an avid composter, but I haven’t been on it like I should.  But that’s the point of this post. To remind myself to do better. 

There are many different ways you can reduce your food waste. But if you’re not going to then the least you can do is compost it. Compost your food waste and convert it into something valuable that your garden will love. Being tight on space is not an acceptable excuse either. There are many different ways to compost in small urban areas. 

I wish I knew how to start one of those viral challenges. I would challenge everyone to record how much food waste they produce in one week and try to find ways to reduce it.

Let’s all do better ✌🏾 

#justgrowit #composting #urbangardener #urbangardening #foodwaste #sustainability

This DIY seed starting light stand comes in handy. Easy to put together and take apart so that you can store it when not in use.

To make it, you will need 
•2 10’ sections of PVC
•8 elbows
•6 T fittings
I used 1/2” because it’s what I had available. Minus the lights, this stand should cost you less than $20 to put together. 

Cut the first 10’ section into the following pieces 
•(2) 40”
•(4) 1.5”
•(2) 7.25”
•(2) 10.5”

Cut the second 10’ section into the following pieces 
•(2) 40”
•(2) 7.25”
•(4) 16.5”

This was a great exercise to see how much food waste my household produced in a week. 
After one week, we ended up with over 15 pounds of food waste. If that were our average weekly waste, we would contribute 60 pounds monthly and 720 pounds yearly. When you say it out loud, it is mind-blowing. 

To reduce food waste, you can: 
1. Shop smarter
2. Utilize your freezer 
3. Start a compost bin 

I plan on starting a few different compost bins that will work in an urban setting. Check me out tomorrow, where I talk about one of my favorite ways to compost ✌🏾

#justgrowit #foodwaste #urbangardener #gardenerlife #houstongardener ##zone9garden #composting

One thing urban gardeners have in common is a lack of space. But that should not stop you from composting. 

Bokashi composting is a great way to compost when you are short on space. All you need is a bucket with a tight lid and bokashi bran. 

Layer your food scraps in a bucket with bokashi bran. This bran is inoculated with microorganisms that ferment or pre compost your veggie scraps. 

After 2-3 weeks in the bucket, you can bury the food waste directly in your garden bed. Unlike other forms
of composting, where you have to watch what you add to the bin. With bokashi, you can compost anything, including meat. 

Bokashi is an anaerobic process, so the only time you should open the bucket is to add food scraps. 

All in all, I’m a big fan of bokashi composting. I will eventually be adding these scraps to my worm bin. 

Give bokashi composting a try.

#justgrowit #bokashi #bokashicomposting #composting #urbangardenspace #urbangardening #gardenlife #houstongarden #zone9garden

Failing to plan is planning to fail 

My dad used to tell me that all the time when I was a kid. I never understood it and wouldn’t listen to him. Now, as an urban gardener, I understand.

If you want to have an efficient and productive garden, you need a plan. Otherwise, you can end up starting too many seeds and being wasteful. Or you don’t buy enough of the specific varieties you wanted. 

I’m not against no plans. Hey, do what works for you. I have had many productive gardens that had no plan. I figured it out by planting whatever I had available. But I’m at the point in my life where I have a plan, and I have to execute the plan. With no plan, there’s no accountability, and I can’t rock like that anymore ✌🏾

#justgrowit #alwaysgrowingfood #urbangardener #zone9garden #houstongardener #gardentips #gardenerlife #gardenplans #alwayshaveaplan

2️⃣ Stems are part of the transportation highway. Water and nutrients are transported from the roots throughout the plants through the stem. 

3️⃣ Strong stems help keep the plant standing tall during rain and wind storms

I have some gardening goals in 2023, and getting rid of all the grass in my yard is one. 

I have already tackled the backyard, so it’s time to move on to the front yard. 

Have you ever stopped and asked yourself why you have a lawn? Or when did lawns become a thing?

Before, I always wanted the greenest grass, but I never thought of the negatives associated with lawns. 

•The Runoff from the pesticides and fertilizers pollutes the water systems 

• the equipment used to maintain the lawns also produces pollution 

• the EPA says 40% of our freshwater resources go to watering lawns.

• lawns are the only crop we water, feed, and maintain that doesn’t give us anything in return. 

Hey, I’m not attacking you if you like your green lawns. Like I always say, do you I just want to know if you have asked yourself why lately.

I don’t care for them and will get rid of mine soon. 

#justgrowit #nomorefrontlawns #alwaysgrowingfood #zone9garden #houstongarden #urbangardener #urbangardening #gardeninspo

Proper lighting is essential when growing seedlings indoors. Without adequate lighting, you will end up with weak and leggy plants. 

Growing your seedlings with proper lighting helps you get a jump start on the next season. 

Now when it comes to lighting, you don’t have to get anything fancy. Simple shop lights will do the trick. What’s important is how close the lights are to the top of the plants. The distance depends on the type of light you are using. 

For fluorescents and led, I would aim for 4”-6” above the plants. For strong lights like hps or mh, you will need more distance between the plants. Really you don’t need those strong lights for seed starting or clones. 

True story-
I usually start my tomatoes outside, and this year I did the same. Unfortunately, here in Houston, sometimes we have  weather that doesn’t know what it wants to do. It will be 80° in the day and low 40s at night. Well, I forgot the tomatoes outside one night when the temperature dropped. A lot of them didn’t make it. It’s a sad day. 
I should have just set up this light from @activegrowled, and I wouldn’t have had this issue. I kept telling myself to move them inside and set up the light, but I just kept making excuses about why I could wait til tomorrow. Well, waiting for tomorrow cost me my plants. 

The moral of the story is to do what you say you’re going to do and stop with the BS ✌🏾

Two of my three apple trees have begun leafing out. While I’m happy to see it, I am worried. 

Fruit trees begin to flower after a cold dormancy period. When you have unpredictable weather, as we have here in Houston, sometimes your trees get fooled and start to leaf out and flower too early. If we get another freeze, then the flowers and new growth are vulnerable. Fluctuations in temperature can shock the tree. 

The Anna apple tree has already put out flowers. Generally, in January, I apply dormant oil spray to the trees, but I guess I missed my window. Alright, that’s enough for tonight. 

Wait, one more thing. If you’re going to plant a fruit tree, do your research and select one that matches the number of chill hours your area receives. If you don’t know about chill hours, check out the episode of Just Grow It- The Podcast where we talk about them. 

Yep, that’s right, I just plugged 🔌 my podcast. 

Now, that’s enough for tonight ✌🏾

After a hard freeze, don’t be so quick to pull plants out of your yard. Plants and trees are incredibly resilient. And sometimes what looks like it is dead may not be. 

Wait til springtime when the temperatures warm up before deciding to remove any spent plants. You never know. It could bounce back. 

I have had plants like certain citrus trees look dead and start to leaf out once the weather changes for the better. I’m not a fan of cold weather. 

Again I’m not telling you what to do—just talking from past experience. But like I always say, do you ✌🏾

Not nearly as many tomatoes as I planned on growing, but that’s ok. 

I started growing my seeds outside and forgot them when the temperatures dropped below 40 degrees. I ended up losing a majority of them. It was too late for me to start more seeds 

But I still have enough for my garden. The garden will be heavy with brandywines and, my favorite, San Marzano. I may even buy a few from the nursery even though I wanted to grow everything in my garden from seed this year. 

It’s time to pot up the remaining tomatoes. Once the tomatoes are a few inches tall and have 2-3 sets of true leaves, it’s time to get them into a larger container. Don’t skip container sizes. If your starting in a seed starting tray or cells, then go to a 4” pot next. Skipping pot sizes may sound like a good idea, but whenever you water the pots, if the roots are not developed enough, you risk the planting medium remaining too moist and drowning your starts. 

Waiting too long to pot up can result in a root-bound plant. Root-bound plants are stressed plants, which can lead to pests and diseases. 

It’s almost tomato time 🍅

I’m getting an early start this year on the sweet potatoes. Last year’s harvest was disappointing, and I will not repeat that. 

Starting your sweet potato slips is easy. Here are two foolproof methods. 

Make sure you’re starting with organic sweet potatoes, not yams. I wanted to grow more purple sweet potatoes, but I had these in the kitchen and couldn’t justify purchasing the purples. 

Method 1 is the water method. Suspend a sweet potato in a mason jar, Ensuring the bottom is slightly submerged in water. Change the water weekly, and in no time, you will have slips.

Method 2 is the soil method. Take a sweet potato and place it on its side in some soil. Keep the soil moist, and in a couple of weeks, you will see slips begin growing. 

Choose whichever method works best for you. Slips take around six weeks to grow. I plan on planting them in April and again in May ✌🏾

Ginger is one of my favorite crops to grow. One reason because I drink ginger tea almost every day and two because it is one of those set it and forget it plants. 

Ginger can be grown in partial shade.
For best results plant in full sun. 

Plant it in loose fertile soil in your garden bed or grow it in containers. Due to the amount of time it takes before harvesting ginger, I prefer growing it in containers.

I usually always order rhizomes.This year I waited too long and they were sold out. So I decided to try my luck with grocery store ginger. I am trying the organic and the conventionally grown.

Before planting outside the Rhizomes should be sprouted for best results. 
Plant a 1-2” piece in warm soil, 72F-80F for 4-6 weeks Usually between February and April depending on the growing zone 
High humidity helps with sprouting . 

Here's a trick someone shared with me; After placing the rhizome in a pot, cover the pot with plastic wrap or a saucer to help increase the humidity. 

If you have never grown ginger give it a try. It may become one of your new favorite crops. 

#justgrowit #alwaysgrowingfood #whatimgrowing #urbangardener #zone9garden #houstongardener

Make sure to harden off your seedlings before transplanting them into the garden. This is an important step that is often overlooked.

Vermicomposting is the process of using worms to break down organic matter.  Not the same worms that you find in your garden.  No, these here are basically super worms. Red Wiggler, or composting worms, can eat up to half their body weight in organic material daily.  Usually, they consume around 25% of their body weight, though.  Imagine if people ate that much!

Worms are housed in a bin with air holes, with bedding material, and are fed kitchen scraps.  They eat the scraps and convert them into worm castings. Castings are the fertile digested “soil” or excrement produced by composting worms. Castings contain a concentrated source of Ca, Mg, N, P, and K, in readily available form.  The castings slowly release the nutrients needed for healthy plant growth throughout all stages of the plant’s life. Castings help improve the soil structure and root zone by contributing to build up the organic matter in the soil/growing medium. This helps strengthen a plant’s immune system and decreases the plant’s vulnerability to pests and diseases. Castings also increase the production rates for all flowers, fruits, and vegetables.

If you’re short on space but still want to compost give vermicomposting a try.

Tomatillos are a member of the nightshade family.  Tomatillos originated in Mexico.  Also known as a husk tomato, these fruits come in various colors, green, purple, red, and orange, to name a few.  These are a staple in my summer garden because they will continue to produce until the year’s first frost.

To produce fruit, you must plant more than two tomatillos in your garden.  This will ensure cross-pollination occurs.

Remember, like their cousin, the tomato, they can root from their stem.  So that means they are easy to clone. Take a branch cutting the same way you would other plants like tomatoes, pothos, and basil. 

Space tomatillos 24” apart due to their sprawling tendencies.  So trellising/ caging is vital, or these plants will spread throughout the garden. 

The fruit forms inside a paper husk known as a calyx, and as the fruit ripens, it will fill in the interior of the husk.  Don’t pick too early, or else the flavor will be bland.

After pruning my second set of tomatoes down, I ended up with a lot of suckers. I have a hard time not doing this, even though I do not have any more space for tomatoes, plus it’s too late, in my opinion, to plant tomatoes. I am still trying to root out these suckers.

Propagating tomato plants from cuttings is extremely easy. Follow the steps:

1. Cut a sucker from the plant at least 4 inches long.
2. Cut that sucker at a 45° angle directly below a node or through a node
3. Remove any flower buds from the sucker.
3. Place the cut sucker in a jar filled with water.
5. Change the water every three days.

After 7 to 10 days, you will see routes start to form on your tomato sucker. Remove from the jar and plant directly into your garden or container.

Propagating tomatoes using this method allows you to get a jumpstart on your fall tomato gardening season. Cut and root desired amount of suckers at the end of the summer. Grow them in a 1 to 3-gallon using this method allows you to get a jumpstart on your fall tomato gardening season.

Top your peppers by cutting the top 1-2 inches off your main stem. This cut forces the plant to focus on creating new growth before flowering. 

New growth will appear at the nodes right next to the remaining leaves. Where you originally had one main branch, now you have two.

I’ve never been the biggest fan of topping peppers. I don’t think I have gotten increased yields due to this technique. I have gotten squattier, bushier plants that didn’t require as much staking. But I have never compared the two results from two plants during the growing season.

Basil is one of my favorite herbs to grow for many different reasons. There are many varieties, so I never get tired of growing it, I can dehydrate it and use it throughout the year, and it is easy to propagate. 

Here's how to propagate basil in water:

1. Take a cutting at least 4” long 

2. Remove the leaves from the bottom third of the plant

3. Place the cuts in a jar of water with the bottom third of the plant submerged. 

4. Place the jar in a spot with bright indirect light. 

5. Change the water daily to prevent bacteria build-up. 

Your cutting should have roots in 7-14 days.

Spent mushroom blocks are one of my favorite things to use in the garden.  If you can get your hands on some give them a try because they work wonders in a garden.  There are still nutrients in this substrate even though it is being thrown away.

  What’s funny is many mushroom farmers will often give them to you for free.

Here are some potential ways to use Mushroom 🍄 Blocks in your garden:

	•Compost- When composted these blocks produce a high quality fungal dominated compost.  And we all known the benefits of fungal compost vs bacterial compost, right?

	•Mulch- By simply placing the spent blocks on the top of the soil, they can act as mulch, like compost. They can help keep weeds at bay and will continue to breakdown and feed the soil.

	•Animal feed- Some of the different substrates are used as forms of animal feed. Whether straw, oat husks, or soybean, the ingredients can already be fed to livestock.

Mulching is one of the most beneficial practices you can use in a garden. Leaving soil exposed to the elements can cause topsoil erosion and promote weed growth.  Mulch protects the ground, providing a protective material layer on top of the soil.

Mulching with spent Mushroom 🍄blocks can 

* Help build healthy soil
* Feed soil organisms 
*Absorb excess water 
*Surpress weeds

It's finally time to begin working on the front yard food forest. 

Usually, I would have dug this grass up, but this current Texas heat is no joke. Instead, I am going to solarize the lawn. 

Solarizing Involves using the heat from the sun to kill everything. Unfortunately, when I say kill everything, I mean it. This method risks killing the beneficials in the soil. So once the grass is dead I will hit up my buddies at @heirloomsoils for some leaf mold compost, then apply it to the area before painting. 

This method takes time and patience and works most effectively during the hot months of the year. With this intensive heat wave I am dealing with, there's plenty of heat for this. 

How to solarize your lawn 

1.	Cover the area with one to two layers of plastic
2.	Secure the plastic edges to ensure wind or animals don’t accidentally remove it. I'm using bags of mulch from @heirloomsoils because I didn't have any bricks near me and I didn't want to be outside any longer than I needed to. 
3.	Leave the plastic in place for 4-12 weeks. The amount of time depends on the temperature in your region. 
4.  After the all it's time remove the tarp, rake the dead grass into a pile and remove and then add some compost to the area. 

Here are some tips for if you plan to go this route
1.	Remove as much plant debris as possible 
2.	Cut the grass as short as possible. This will help shorten the time necessary to complete the process.
3.	Water the area before starting. When covered, this will create a steam effect and kill the grass faster. 

I should be ready to start planting this area at the end of September.

Fall time is a great time to plant fruit trees in your garden. 

When purchasing a new fruit tree, here are a few things to think about.

1. Will this tree grow well in my area? Different fruit trees thrive in different environments. When purchasing, ask yourself, can this variety withstand the temperature, humidity, and overall weather of the region?

2. Is the tree healthy? I always check the trunk for any wounds or cracks. I want healthy branches with evenly spaced buds and no signs of disease or pests. 

3. How old is this fruit tree? Younger trees take longer to bear fruit but can establish stronger roots and respond better when transplanted. 
I love that mature trees can offer immediate fruit, but I prefer to plant younger trees. 

4. Don’t forget about pollination.  Some varieties need cross-pollination for optimal fruit production. There’s nothing worse than a big fruit tree with no fruit. 

I have certain things I look for when purchasing new fruit trees, but I have always wondered what other people check for.

Garlic needs to be exposed to cold temperatures to form bulbs. This typically happens for fall-planted garlic when exposed to winter temperatures.

But if you live in southern climates or places with mild winters, winter temperatures may not be cold enough to complete the vernalization process. 

So, to trick the bulbs into thinking they have experienced the cold exposure process. Store your garlic in the refrigerator for at least 40 days before planting.

Since I live in the southern part of the United States, I grow short-day onions. These onions need between 10 to 12 hours of sunlight to begin forming bulbs. But if you live anywhere else, like up north, you want long-day onions Instead of short-day onions.

These onions should be ready to harvest in about 100 days.

Trellising blackberries is a great way to help increase your yield by improving airflow and keeping the canes and fruit off the ground. 

To create this easy DIY trellis, I used:
• 2 leftover 4 x 4
•16 gauge wire 
•4 screw eyes 
•2 turnbuckles

I concreted the post into the ground because I needed to reattach the @hoselinkusa to one of the posts.

This is the easiest way to make sure you have the perfect-sized hole to plant your fruit trees. 

•Place the fruit tree, still in the container, at your desired depth 
•Backfill the hole with soil. 
•Remove the potted container from the middle, and you will be left with the perfect planting hole.
